diff:1670117893:1670117893:=1,90d0%0a%3c (:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0a%3c Status: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!{$:Category}]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Mapudungun%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: akshaychekuri%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Endanged Mapudungun Language of Mapuche People of Chile%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Mapudungun is a language in the Araucanian language family, primarily spoken by the Mapuche people in Central Chile. Note that the name "Araucanian" is somewhat controversial within the Mapuche community due to its origins in Spanish colonialism. Historically, Mapudungun was the dominant language of this region, acting as a sort of lingua franca to other groups of people across modern-day Chile and Argentina. %0a%3c %0a%3c As recently as 2010, there are about 250,000 speakers of Mapudungun left in the world, with 200,000 in Chile and 50,000 in Argentina. However, more recent trends indicate that this number may be much lower. Furthermore, many of those counted as "speakers" are more so passive speakers. The primary cause of this decline was initially discrimination of the Mapuche people and discouragement of them using their native language by colonizers. In a sense, this continues in the modern day as Mapudungun has yet to be recognized as an official language in either Chile or Argentina despite being the dominant language of the region for centuries. Since it has never been an official language, it hasn't entered the curriculum of schools and thus essentially the only way the language is preserved is through home languages. However, many of the remaining households of Mapudungun speakers are small-scale farmers and in an increasingly urbanized world, the number of such households is decreasing each year.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mapuche_language%0a%3c https://www.languagesgulper.com/eng/Mapudungun.html%0a%3c https://www.academia.edu/3234126%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a%3c !!Change article category%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:Section: D:)%0a%3c (:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)%0a%3c (:Title: Mapudungun:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
